doxia/doxia-core/index.json:33:    \"description\" : \"Apache Maven Doxia Core provides the central classes and interfaces for Doxia, Maven's content generation framework for producing static and dynamic content from multiple markup formats. It includes parser, sink, macro, indexing, and utility infrastructure used by Doxia modules to transform documents into output formats.\",\nmetadata/com.thoughtworks.proxytoys/proxytoys/index.json:9:    \"description\" : \"ProxyToys provides an implementation-neutral Java proxy API that lets applications switch between JDK dynamic proxies and CGLIB proxies. It also includes factory-style utilities for common proxy patterns such as decorators, delegates, dispatchers, failover objects, futures, hot swapping, multicasting, null objects, pooling, and privileged invocation.\",\nmetadata/org.apache.pekko/pekko-actor_2.13/1.1.5/reachability-metadata.json:33:        \"typeReached\" : \"org.apache.pekko.actor.ReflectiveDynamicAccess\"\nmetadata/org.apache.pekko/pekko-actor_2.13/1.1.5/reachability-metadata.json:47:        \"typeReached\" : \"org.apache.pekko.actor.ReflectiveDynamicAccess\"\nmetadata/org.apache.pekko/pekko-actor_2.13/1.1.5/reachability-metadata.json:62:        \"typeReached\" : \"org.apache.pekko.actor.ReflectiveDynamicAccess\"\nmetadata/org.apache.pekko/pekko-actor_2.13/1.1.5/reachability-metadata.json:78:        \"typeReached\" : \"org.apache.pekko.actor.ReflectiveDynamicAccess\"\nmetadata/org.apache.pekko/pekko-actor_2.13/1.1.5/reachability-metadata.json:88:            \"org.apache.pekko.actor.DynamicAccess\"\nmetadata/org.neo4j.driver/neo4j-java-driver/5.28.5/reachability-metadata.json\nmetadata/org.neo4j.driver/neo4j-java-driver/index.json\n"}], "isError": false, "timestamp": 1782719857390}}
[recv] {"type": "turn_end", "message": {"role": "assistant", "content": [{"type": "thinking", "thinking": "**Evaluating Neo4j and Docker Requirements**\n\nI'm considering the need for meaningful coverage of core driver operations using Neo4j via Docker. For reachability metadata, I might manage without a server using value mapping and driver creation. However, there's a current issue with Java-run tests not related to a new library. It seems the existing library already has tests without needing Docker unless the generated tests require it. I want to check existing upstream tests and see if Testcontainers can help. Maybe connecting to localhost for testing would work better.\n\n**Assessing Neo4j Driver Requirements**\n\nI'm thinking about how the driver connects to the Neo4j graph database via Bolt. To execute a query, I definitely need a server, which makes Docker necessary. However, the existing test suite in the repo avoids using a server on purpose. The issue seems to be with the Java run, possibly not coverage related. I wonder if the driver can achieve meaningful coverage only when a server is involved. It might be worthwhile to inspect the current dynamic access coverage.", "thinkingSignature": "{\"id\":\"rs_037ff3bfaf2c2296016a422569f010819483b2718c870bfe42\",\"type\":\"reasoning\",\"content\":[],\"encrypted_content\":\"gAAAAABqQiVwtBb1A1V-jAWlM1lxqGJSc2n7yjhtEILhjxXP7Uo40nV5JpB1A97-fhPWYj773XsWydJNlUft8WqqSSxWz4LV2L576MPnFF-PLipfUkFFmNML3eIXxBfHzh9RMMf-EGeoFHTClY5Y5dNwGIWAi0wN4KYbKxB9fhl2X7cb6qqY3OQMliMW7CVwuytghaEpvynlGu_nfNKL1owkvw5RL-8uudSRVtLxoo6fGKfdO4pjU6nSNRblP-Z5efiPf0cuvCWH0mULalKKn7uxaex2KyaWU8NC-i3cfv3lvDoBhkNcyonTzaCej08UCUj09w4ljcoy4deaOe_RSXVsgULerne4WANlQWvqn5BasjyCVilRliBaYlBBZKCmUlYbPrTOc5-p75QqJEk0Gp7vtRblbRJAqym7MSAxw4QkdCu6pvHgUtwbjM_wO4NGap38hBCi4MJdWa9ui0eRUX3fIs83MBQ6jkW4aYbW2theKrlSqfLvUz5mvp15FG4qu9AuY2St-EewpDkNpUBEH1hIzbqqgE26XtqaU0NvIuCfAz7zhxGNflYSO6EOBUvXFWVEksdq02OvS9zWqO8E0sP78s4uXqFgbF4ydi_M0k8iA45uFXoiaCmNBJ0hUES5pgB5T-XvBD